            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>
                    [On the 14th day before the Kalends of September, the day that Caesar] undertook his first consulate, [a supplication to ????].
                    [On the 3rd day before the Nones of September, the day] Lepidus surrendered his army to Caesar, a supplication [to ????].
                    [On the 9th day before the Kalends of October], the birthday of Caesar, a sacrifice of an animal to Caesar and a supplication [to ????].
                    On the Nones of October, the birthday of Drusus Caesar, a supplication to Vesta.
                    On the 15th day before the Kalends of November, the day that Caesar assumpted the toga virilis, a supplication to Spes and Iuventas.
                    On the 16th day before the Kalends of December, the birthday of Tiberius Caesar, a supplication to Vesta.
                    On the 18th day before the Kalends of January, the day that the altar of Fortuna Redux was dedicated, who brought Caesar back from his provinces [across the seas], a supplication to Fortuna Redux.
                    On the 7th day before the Ides of January, the [day that Caesar] first assumed the fasces, a supplication to Jupiter Sempiternus.
                    On the 18th day before the Kalends of February, the day that [Caesar] was named [Augustus], a supplication to Augustus.
                    [On the 3rd day before the Kalends of February, the day that the Ara Pacis was dedicated], a supplication to the imperium of Caesar Augustus, the guardian [of Roman citizens and the world]
                    [On the day before the Nones of March, the day that Caesar] was made [pontifex] maximus, a supplication to Vesta, the public Penates of the Roman people, the Quirites.
                    [On the 18th day before the Kalends of May, the day Caesar first conquered], a supplication to Victoria Augusta.
                    [On the 17th day before the Kalends of May, the day Caesar was first] saluted [imperator], a supplication to Felicitas of empire.
                    [On the 4th day before the Ides of May, the day the temple of Mars was dedicated], a supplication to Mars' Moles.
                    [On the 9th day before the Kalends of June, the birthday of Germanicus Caesar], a supplication to Vesta.
                    [On the 4th day before the Ides of July, the birthday of the divine Julius, a supplication of Jupiter], Mars the Avenger, and Venus [the Ancestress].
                    [----] a supplication to Jupiter [----].   
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>This sacred calendar of Cumae exclusively celebrates supplications and sacrifices on important dates for the imperial household (Caesar Augustus, Tiberius Caesar, Drusus Caesar and the Julius Caesar). Of note here are the various deities 
                    thought responsible for the successes of Augustus and his family, as well as direct supplications and animal sacrifice to Caesar/Augustus himself as a god. Lomas (1996, 192) suggests that the reason the calendar appears to start with August 
                    was that it was 'common practice for Italian cities to take the date of Augustus' first visit to them as their New Year'.</p> 
                <!-- Taylor 1920, 199; Gradel 2002, 96; Fishwick 1991f, 490, 509-510; Hemelrijk 2007, 327; BNP 2 no. 3.4 -->
            </div>
